**Comparing Strings in Java**

In Java, there are two ways to compare strings: using the `==` operator and the `.equals()` method.

### 1. Using the `==` Operator

The `==` operator checks if two strings refer to the same object in memory. It returns `true` if the strings are the same object and `false` otherwise.

### 2. Using the `.equals()` Method

The `.equals()` method compares the actual values of two strings. It returns `true` if the strings have the same characters in the same order and `false` otherwise.

### When to Use Each Method

- Use the `==` operator when you want to check if two strings refer to the same object in memory.
- Use the `.equals()` method when you want to compare the actual values of two strings.

### Differences Between the Two Methods

- The `==` operator checks if two strings refer to the same object in memory.
- The `.equals()` method compares the actual values of two strings.

### Example
```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

// Using the == operator
if (str1 == str2) {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 refer to the same object.");
} else {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 refer to different objects.");
}

// Using the .equals() method
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same characters in the same order.");
} else {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 do not have the same characters in the same order.");
}
```

### Conclusion

- Use the `==` operator when you want to check if two strings refer to the same object in memory.
- Use the `.equals()` method when you want to compare the actual values of two strings.

